        <!-- Authority Bias: Using a high-ranking title and the threat of a negative consequence -->
        <p>As the Chief Information Security Officer, I am requiring all staff to re-authenticate their single sign-on (SSO) credentials to ensure the new security protocols are properly applied to your account. Failure to do so by end of day will result in a temporary lock on your workstation.</p>

        <p>Please use the secure portal link below to verify your access immediately:</p>

        <a onclick="javascript:return false;" href="https://generic-training-link.example.com/" style="display:inline-block;background-color:#D32F2F;color:#FFFFFF;text-align:center;padding:12px 24px;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold;border-radius:4px;">Verify Account Access</a>

        <p>Thank you for helping us keep [Your Company Name] secure.</p>

        <p>Sincerely,</p>
        <p><strong>Alex Mercer</strong><br>Chief Information Security Officer (CISO)<br>[Your Company Name]</p>
    </div>
</body>
```

### Breakdown of the Biases Used:

*   **Familiarity Bias:** The email addresses the user by their first name and references a plausible shared experience ("recent department-wide software migration," "last week's all-hands meeting"). This makes the context feel routine and internal, lowering the target's guard.
*   **Authority Bias:** The sender claims to be the "Chief Information Security Officer (CISO)" and uses directive language ("requiring all staff," "needs your immediate assistance"). It also introduces an artificial time constraint and a penalty for non-compliance ("Failure to do so by end of day will result in a temporary lock"), which pressures the target to act quickly rather than verifying the request.

